Motivation

In this project, I analyzed a data set about the price per area unit of real estate in the Sindian region in New Taipei city. The goal is to make the price of real estate predictable based on its location and some extra information described in the data section. Furthermore, I made a Shiny application with the following functionalities: 1. An interactive map showing the price per unit for the real estate in the data set. The users can select the price range that they want to see to filter the available data. Also, the price of the real estate is shown by hovering over their location. The circles on the map showing the real estate locations are correlated in size with the unit price of the real estate. 2. An interactive scatter plot in which the user decides the variables to show on the x and y axes. 3. A clustering tab that clusters the real estates based on their x and y coordinates and the number of clusters can be modified by the user. 4. A linear regression tab in which the user can choose the independent variable and the regression model (between the options of linear regression and logarithmic regression). The app reports the \(R^2\) measure of the chosen regression model between the price per unit of the real estate and the chosen independent variable. 5. A table showing the used data set in which the user can also look for specific data by using the search box.

Data

The chosen data set has 414 samples of real estate information. Each sample contains the following information about the real estate: Inputs: X1 = the transaction date (for example, 2013.250=2013 March, 2013.500=2013 June, etc.) X2 = the house age (unit: year) X3 = the distance to the nearest MRT station (unit: meter) X4 = the number of convenience stores in walking distance (integer) X5 = the geographic coordinate, latitude. (unit: degree) X6 = the geographic coordinate, longitude. (unit: degree) Output: Y = house price of unit area (10000 New Taiwan Dollar/Ping, where Ping is a local unit, 1 Ping = 3.3 meter squared)

App usage

The Map tab

  1. The circles on the map are proportional in size to the unit price of the real estate.
  2. By hovering on the circles on the map, you can see the unit price.
  3. By changing the price range in the slide bar, you can set the map to only show the real estate within the selected price range.

The Scatter Plots tab

For a given variable on the x axis and a given variable on the y axis, the scatter plot will be shown.

The Clusters tab

  1. The data is clustered based on the longitude and latitude values.
  2. By setting the number of clusters, you can see the k-means result for the chosen number of clusters.

The Regression tab

  1. The regression model can be chosen. The supported options are Linear and Logarithmic.
  2. The independent variable (among the inputs) can be chosen.
  3. The output is the \(R^2\) value of the chosen regression.

The Data tab

  1. You can read and search in the data used in this project.
  2. The link to access the origial data from UCI is provided.

Clustering

I cluster the dataset based on the geographic longitude and latitude of the samples. To do so, I first run the K-means clustering algorithm for 2 through 20 clusters and plot the Sum of Squared Errors (SSE) against the number of clusters to choose the best number of clusters for this dataset. K-means algorithm clusters into K groups. It starts from K random points (centers) and assigns each sample to the cluster for its closest center. Once all the samples are assigned to a cluster, the centers are recalculated based on the average of the samples in their clusters and the cluster assignment will run again. This process iterates continually until the centers don’t change.

realEstate_data = realEstate %>% select(matches("latitude"), matches("longitude"), matches("unitPrice"))

km = kmeans(realEstate_data$unitPrice, centers=1)
wss = km$tot.withinss

numOfK = 20
# Find out SSE for clusters 2 to 20
for (i in 2:numOfK)
  wss[i] = kmeans(realEstate_data$unitPrice, centers=i)$tot.withinss

# Plot SSE vs. Number of Clusters
sse = data.frame(c(1:numOfK), c(wss))
names(sse)[1] = 'Clusters'
names(sse)[2] = 'SSE'
sse %>%
  ggvis(~Clusters, ~SSE) %>%
  layer_points(fill := 'blue') %>% 
  layer_lines() %>%
  set_options(height = 300, width = 400)

According to the previous part, 7 is a good choice for the number of clusters for this dataset. In the following I run the K-means clustering algorithm for K=7 and plot the result:

clusters = kmeans(realEstate_data[,1:2], 7)

### Assign Labels
realEstate_data$Cluster = clusters$cluster

### Plot Clusters
plot(realEstate_data[,1:2],
     col = clusters$cluster,
     pch = 20, cex = 3)

Regression

In this parts, I find a model in which one can predict the price per unit area of the real estate based on information about the real estate. The supported models are linear and logarithmic regression. Linear regression: \[y_{i} = \alpha + \beta.x_{i}\] Logarithmic regression: \[y_{i} = \alpha + \beta.ln(x_{i})\]

To evaluate the model, the \(R^{2}\) value is used which can be calculated based on the predicted residual sum of squares (PRESS) and total sum of squares (SST) described in the following formulas. The closer the \(R^{2}\) value is to one, the better the model behaves. \[SST = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y^{ref}_{i}-y^{mean}_{i})^{2}\] \[PRESS = \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y^{ref}_{i}-y^{pred}_{i})^{2}\] \[R^{2} = 1 - \frac{PRESS}{SST}\]

In the first part, I find a regression model between the price per unit area and the distance from the real estate to the nearest MRT station.

## F-statistic: 2.464 on 1 and 330 DF,  p-value: 0.1174
## test:
predPrice = data.frame(predict(lr, newdata=testSet))
colnames(predPrice)[1] = 'Predicted'
predPrice$Reference = testSet[,c('unitPrice')]
predPrice$Predicted <- unlist(predPrice$Predicted)
predPrice$Reference <- unlist(predPrice$Reference)
p3 = qplot(Reference, Predicted, data=predPrice) + geom_point(colour = "#006600", size = 3)
p3

## evaluation:
PRESS = sum((predPrice$Reference - predPrice$Predicted)^2, na.rm = TRUE)
SST = sum((predPrice$Reference - mean(predPrice$Reference))^2, na.rm = TRUE)
R2 = 1 - (PRESS/SST)
print(paste0("R2 = ", R2))
## [1] "R2 = 0.00561554161692146"

With geographical coordinates

In the fourth part, I find a regression model between the price per unit area and the geographical coordinates of the real estate.

## calc. the x and y coordinates based on longitude and latitude
realEstate$xcoord <- latlong2grid(cbind(realEstate$longitude,realEstate$latitude))$x
realEstate$ycoord <- latlong2grid(cbind(realEstate$longitude,realEstate$latitude))$y
realEstate$rcoord <- sqrt(realEstate$xcoord^2 + realEstate$ycoord^2)

## run and evaluate the model

Multi-variable regression

Finally, I find a regression model based on all of the independent variables evaluated in the previous parts.

## split the data to generate the train and test data sets:
set.seed(324)
splitPrice = caret::createDataPartition(realEstate$unitPrice, p = 0.8, list=F, times=1)
trainSet = realEstate[splitPrice,]
testSet = realEstate[-splitPrice,]


## train
lr = lm(unitPrice ~ lnMRTDist + numStores + lnAge + TXDate + xcoord + ycoord, data=trainSet)

Conclusion

There is a significant improvement in the multi-variable regression model compared to the single-variable ones. The \(R^2\) for the multi-varialbe is around 0.7 whereas the maximum number for \(R^2\) in single-variable models was 0.52 (belonging to the logarithm of the closest MRT station distance).
